 began 50 years earlier) and would create a storm that would preface the ne=
w one. &nbsp;Roosevelt, facing a similar moment, crafted himself for the mo=
ment. A vastly wealth man, who knew nothing of the poor, he nevertheless cr=
afted himself as the friend of the poor, and was treated as a traitor to&nb=
sp; his class. &nbsp;Among his 99 Executive orders were some that wrecked t=
